'''Wa no Mutsu Agata''' (倭の六県, also known as '''Roku no Miagata''') refers to six directly governed territories of the {{ill|Great King|ja|治天下大王|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (imperial family) in ancient {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

On {{ill|August 5, 645|ja|8月5日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (first year of the {{ill|Taika|ja|大化|qq=draft|qq=draft}} era), messengers were dispatched alongside provincial officials in the eastern provinces to conduct household registration and land surveys.<ref>''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', Volume 25, entry on {{ill|Emperor Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Taika 1st Year.</ref>

The "Six Counties" correspond to the following districts as listed in ''{{ill|Wamyō Ruijushō|ja|和名類聚抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'':

* '''Sofu (Soe) County''' (曽布・添県) - {{ill|Soegami District|ja|添上郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Soeshimo District|ja|添下郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* '''Yamanobe County''' (山辺県) - {{ill|Yamanobe District|ja|山辺郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* '''Shiki County''' (磯城県) - {{ill|Shikijō District|ja|式上郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shikige District|ja|式下郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* '''Tōchi County''' (十市県) - {{ill|Tōchi District|ja|十市郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* '''Takechi County''' (高市県) - {{ill|Takechi District|ja|高市郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* '''Katsuragi County''' (葛城県) - {{ill|Katsujō District|ja|葛上郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Katsuge District|ja|葛下郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

Within these areas, several shrines bearing the name of their respective counties were established as {{ill|Shikinai shrines|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, including:
* {{ill|Soe Mikenoza Shrine|ja|添御県坐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Nara City, Miutsuka and Utahime)
* {{ill|Yamanobe Mikenoza Shrine|ja|山邊御県坐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Tenri City, Bessho and Nishiidodō)
* {{ill|Shiki Mikenoza Shrine|ja|志貴御県坐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Sakurai City, Miwa Kanaya)
* {{ill|Tōchi Mikenoza Shrine|ja|十市御縣坐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kashihara City, Tōchi)
* {{ill|Takechi Mikenoza Shrine|ja|高市御県神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kashihara City, Shijō)
* {{ill|Katsuragi Mikenoza Shrine|ja|葛木御県神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Katsuragi City, Katsuragi)

Among the 27 prayers listed in the ''{{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', the {{ill|Kinensai|ja|祈年祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Harvest Prayer Festival) specifically mentions offerings from these six counties, primarily vegetables. The six counties occupied the entirety of the {{ill|Nara Basin|ja|奈良盆地|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, but their extent was not vast.

In {{ill|624|ja|624th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (32nd year of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), {{ill|Soga no Umako|ja|蘇我馬子|qq=draft|qq=draft}} petitioned Empress Suiko to grant him Katsuragi County as a private estate, citing it as the ancestral homeland of the Soga clan and the origin of their noble title ("Omi"). However, the empress, despite being of Soga descent, rejected the request.<ref>''Nihon Shoki'', Volume 22, entry on Empress Suiko, 32nd Year, 10th Month.</ref>

